              <h4>Sir Maurice Wilkes</h4>

              <p>The father of British computing died peacefully around 7am on Monday
              29th November aged 97. <a href=
              "http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-11875821">BBC News writes</a>. The
              Register, biting the hand that feeds IT, reports <a href=
              "http://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/11/30/maurice_wilkes_rip/">Wilkes
              reaches EOL</a>. Obituaries from <a href=
              "%20http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2010/nov/30/sir-maurice-wilkes-obituary">
              Guardian</a>, <a href=
              "http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/maurice-wilkes-visionary-and-pioneering-doyen-of-british-computing-2147811.html">
              Independent</a>, <a href=
              "http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/technology-obituaries/8171435/Professor-Sir-Maurice-Wilkes.html">
              Telegraph</a> and <a href=
              "http://www.bcs.org/server.php?show=conWebDoc.38150">British Computer
              Society</a>.</p>

              <p>In 2004 <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Wilkes">Sir
              Maurice</a> gave his "<a href=
              "http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/archive/mvw1/Progress_in_Computers_IEE_Cambridge_2004_web.pdf">Progress
              in Computers</a>" to the Cambridge Computer Lab. The clarity of his views
              are a model for us all.</p>
