              <h4>"Database State": Rountree Reform Trust on UK Government IT</h4>

              <p>David Shutt, Lord Shutt of Greetland, Chair of the <a href=
              "http://www.jrrt.org.uk/">Joseph Rowntree Reform Trust Ltd.</a> states</p>

              <div style="margin-left:5%">
                <p>"Of the 46 databases assessed in this report only six are given the
                green light. That is, only six are found to have a proper legal basis for
                any privacy intrusions and are proportionate and necessary in a
                democratic society. Nearly twice as many are almost certainly illegal
                under human rights or data protection law and should be scrapped or
                substantially redesigned, while the remaining 29 databases have
                significant problems and should be subject to an independent review".</p>
              </div>

              <p>The assessment team from the <a href="http://www.fipr.org/">Foundation
              for Information Policy Research</a> included <a href=
              "http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~rja14/">Professor Ross Anderson</a>, Professor of
              Security Engineering at the Cambridge Computer Laboratory.</p>

              <p>Download .pdf "<a href="database-state.pdf">Database State</a>".</p>

              <p>UK <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transformational_Government">Transformational
              Government</a> programme.</p>
              <hr />

