              <hr />

              <h4>Stephen Wolfram describes WolframAlpha knowledge search engine</h4>

              <p>Wolfram's <a href=
              "http://nextbigfuture.com/2009/05/wolfram-alpha-in-action-video.html">YouTube
              video</a> gives a fascinating insight into the first release of his
              <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/">WolframAlpha</a> computational
              knowledge project.</p>

              <p>There are four main parts of the system. The first "curates" data input,
              then methods of computation collected from his earlier <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematica%3EMathematica">Mathematica</a>
              and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_New_Kind_of_Science">New Kind
              of Science</a> project are applied. A linguistic analysis/understanding
              module, for which he claims ambiguity resolution easier than expected,
              interprets input queries and an automatic formatting engine sends the
              answer to the user. There will be both free and subscription access.</p>

              <p>In his <a href=
              "http://blog.wolfram.com/2009/03/05/wolframalpha-is-coming/">personal
              blog</a> Wolfram claims "That almost gets us to what people thought
              computers would be able to do 50 years ago!"</p>

              <p>BBC News gathers first use <a href=
              "http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/8055160.stm">impressions from
              experts</a>.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4>Lovelock interviewed by Nature</h4>

              <p>Nature's chief News and Features editor, Oliver Morton, <a href=
              "http://www.nature.com/nature/videoarchive/lovelock/">interviews James
              Lovelock</a> on the the possibility of the imminent collapse of Earth's
              human ecosystem. Lovelock notes seven climate events reducing Earth's human
              population in the first million years of man's evolution.</p>

              <p>Nature's <a href="http://www.nature.com/nature/videoarchive/">video
              archive</a>.</p>
