              <h4>Lovelock says slow pyrolysis and burial of agricultiural waste could
              save the earth</h4>

              <p>"But I bet they won't do it" he says in an interview in <a href=
              "http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20126921.500-one-last-chance-to-save-mankind.html">
              New Scientist (24th January 2009)</a>. The scheme requires no subsidy and
              could produce small amounts of biofuel for sale.</p>

              <p>The idea is for farmers to burn or <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biochar">"biochar"</a> their waste and by
              controlling the air level produce charcoal. The charcoal must then be
              buried.</p>

              <p>We trust <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variety_(cybernetics)#The_Law_of_Requisite_Variety">
              Requisite Variety</a> is satisfied.</p>

              <p>James Lovelock FRS is an Honorary Fellow of the Cybernetics Society. He
              warns global warming will produce famine and could lead to a world
              population of less than a billion in a hundred years from now.</p>

              <p>From <a href=
              "http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1864279,00.html">Time</a>
              magazine last December "Cornell's <a href=
              "http://www.css.cornell.edu/faculty/lehmann.htmlLehmann">Lehmann</a> is
              even more emphatic."If biochar could be massively applied around the
              globe," he says, "we could end the emissions problem in one to two
              years.""</p>

              <p>This is a <a href=
              "http://orgprints.org/13268/01/Biochar_as_a_soil_amendment_-_a_review.pdf">detailed
              review</a> by Dominic Woolf from Swansea University.</p>

              <p><a href="http://www.biochar-international.org/">International Biochar
              Initiative</a> formed in 2006.</p>
              <hr />

