              <h4>Lovelock on Climate change at the Royal Society</h4>

              <p>Our <a href=
              "http://www.cybsoc.org/about-soc/honorary-fellows.htm">honorary fellow</a>
              Professor <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Lovelock">James
              Lovelock</a> discusses the response of the earth to global warming and
              possible interventions from the perspective of his <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaia_hypothesis">Gaia model</a>. "A feedback
              or cybernetic system which seeks an optimal physical and chemical
              environment for life on this planet". Video of lecture "<a href=
              "http://www.royalsoc.ac.uk/event.asp?id=7142&amp;month=10,2007">Climate
              change on the living Earth</a>" (1:05:29 Real Player or Windows Media
              Player).</p>
              <hr />

              <h4>Emotion Machine: Commonsense Thinking, Artificial Intelligence, and the
              Future of the Human Mind</h4>

              <p>Marvin Minsky <a href="http://mitworld.mit.edu/video/484/">talks on
              video</a> (1:23:10 Real Player) at MIT about the problems of AI and his
              latest book. Visit Minsky's <a href=
              "http://web.media.mit.edu/~minsky/">website</a> to download the 2006
              version along with many other of his publications. The sound is of variable
              quality but the setting of goals, the detection of difference, the building
              of analogies and the context dependency of interpretation has a
              contemporary ring in <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Pask">Pask's</a> work. Minsky's use of
              critics and selectors on his suggested six level model is redolent of more
              English cybernetics in <a href=
              "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stafford_Beer">Beer's</a> VSM.</p>
              <hr />

