              <h4 align="center">"<a name="laughlin" class="plain" href=
              "http://large.stanford.edu/rbl/lectures/index.htm" id="laughlin">Principles
              of organization are what really make our world knowable not theories of
              everything</a>"</h4>

              <p><a href="http://large.stanford.edu/rbl/index.htm">Prof. Robert B.
              Laughlin</a> won the Nobel prize in 1998 with St&ouml;rmer and Tsui "for
              their discovery of a new form of quantum fluid with fractionally charged
              excitations". In his talk discussing "<a href=
              "http://large.stanford.edu/rbl/lectures/index.htm">The Self-Organization of
              matter</a>" Laughlin says of the pathological limitations of serial
              mathematics and computing methods "Unfortunately, the latter [theory of
              everything equations] cannot be tested because the problem is bigger than
              any computer that now exists, or even any computer that can ever be built."
              This has led to the <a href=
              "http://online.itp.ucsb.edu/online/glasses_c03/kitaev/">Anyon</a> Calculus-
              but there is still no formal concurrent methodology in the Physics
              Community. In many respects Structural Engineers come closest to modelling
              this level of complexity.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4 align="center" id="htsah"><a class="plain" href=
              "http://www.hrat.btinternet.co.uk/Homeostat.html">Dr. Horace Townsend
              simulates<br />
              Ashby's Homeostat</a></h4>

              <p>Dr. Townsend is a retired Clinical Neuorologist developing a site on the
              interpretation of <a href=
              "http://www.hrat.btinternet.co.uk/index.html">Electroencephalograms</a>.
              The Java applet simulates a four pen chart recorder with perturbable
              pens.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4 align="center">"<a class="plain" href="lkonthevoid.htm">Fragments of
              the Void-Selecta</a>"<br />
              by Professor Louis Kauffman</h4>

              <p>In the course of wide-ranging discussions on Forces in Cybernetics
              Professor Kauffman, introduced us to his new paper <b>"Non-Commutative
              Calculus and Discrete Physics", <a href=
              "http://www2.math.uic.edu/~kauffman/NCP.pdf">[A,B] = AB - BA</a> .</b></p>

              <p>He also gave us a quote from <b>"Fragments of the Void-Selecta"</b>.
              "The paragraphs are intended as intense little excursions into thoughts on
              the edge of the void, near the simplicity of one distinction or no
              distinction at all", he says.</p>

              <p>He kindly agreed to publish it <a href="lkonthevoid.htm">here</a> as
              part of out Winter Solstice celebration.</p>

              <p>Lou also drew attention to <a href=
              "http://www.cs.ubc.ca/nest/imager/contributions/scharein/KnotSquare.html">Knot
              Plot</a>: first class software from Rob Scharein. A model example of
              documentation and support for those interested in knots or who would like
              to know more. You can download <a href=
              "http://www.colab.sfu.ca/KnotPlot/exhibits/">Knot Plot</a> and its
              documentation to run on most machines. Load 6.3.2 will load a Pask
              Borromean concept/continuity model and minimising the energy or relaxing
              the link (select energy, undamped dynamics, and allow collisions) you will
              see some of the vibrational modes. The difficulties of simulating
              concurrence which this software attempts should not be underestimated.</p>

              <p>To make a Borromean Link select the Braid tab on Control Panel. Set
              ngens at 6, nstrings at 3 and click aBaBaB and click Close. Select Main and
              click Go. Your Pask cybernetic model of learning continuity well relax in
              front of your eyes.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4 align="center">"<a class="plain" href=
              "http://www.wavestonepress.co.uk/photo_934703.html">Stafford Beer: A
              personal memoir</a>"</h4>

              <p>This affectionate memoir from David Whittaker has a short <a href=
              "http://www.cybsoc.org/contacts/people-Beer.htm#david">review</a> on
              Stafford's <a href=
              "http://www.cybsoc.org/contacts/people-Beer.htm">Memorial</a> page. Highly
              recommended.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4 align="center"><a class="plain" href=
              "http://www.openmind.org/commonsense">Open Mind Project</a></h4>

              <p>After the under achievements (" <a class="plain" href=
              "http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/11.08/view.html?pg=3">Not there
              yet</a>" Minsky) of Lenat's <a href="http://www.cyc.com//">Cycorp</a>, MIT
              has launched an attempt at A.I. by directly collecting commonsense rules to
              explain story scenarios. Pask's I.A. was in part set up to repair the
              deficiencies in A.I. research but Minsky thinks serial machines can
              simulate minds without Pask field concurrence. You can <a href=
              "http://www.openmind.org/commonsense">contribute</a> to the new approach
              which is a model of clean design.</p>
              <hr />

              <h4 align="center"><a class="plain" href=
              "http://www.royalsoc.ac.uk/events/">Forthcoming Royal Society Two Day
