              <h4>Web Lectures</h4>
              <hr />

              <p class="side">MIT's OpenCourseWare <a href=
              "http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/index.htm">Homepage</a></p>

              <p class="side">Videoed Physics Lectures</p>

              <p>e.g Prof Walter Lewin on <a href=
              "http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/Physics/8-02Electricity-and-MagnetismSpring2002/CourseHome/index.htm">
              Electricity and Magnetism</a> comes highly recommended by our member Tony
              Booth</p>

              <p>There is a wealth of material.</p>
              <hr />

              <p><a href="http://www.eng.uci.edu/faculty_research/profile/mmadou">Marc
              Madou</a> on <a href="http://mmadou.eng.uci.edu/">Micro-Electro-Mechanical
              Systems</a></p>
              <hr />

              <p class="side">Richard Feynman's <a href=
              "http://www.vega.org.uk/series/lectures/feynman/index.html">lectures on
              QED</a>, his theory of Quantum Electrodynamics. Four lectures of an hour
              and a half each by the Master. An absolute delight. Essential to those
              interested in circular processes, information and its interactions with
              matter. This is a useful introduction to the more recent Penrose approach
              to force in his <a href=
              "http://online.kitp.ucsb.edu/online/gravity99/penrose/">Twistor Theory</a>.
              This work sets the context for Pask's more accessible theory of
              self-organisation and learning <a href=
              "http://www.nickgreen.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/PIA2.PDF">Interactions of
              Actors</a>.</p>

